","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William John Stacey was born about 1375, in Biddenden, Kent, England, his father, Thomas Stacy, was 22 and his mother, Lady Joanna de Tyldenne, was 22. He married Agatha Alice Bendish about 1400, in Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1401, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1375–1401":"umbes 1375–1401","1375–1401":"1375–1401","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1379–Male":"1379–Surnud","1381–Male":"1381–Surnud","1379–1466":"1379–1466","1401–1431":"1401–1431","1403–Male":"1403–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1407–Female":"1407–Surnud",